    <h1>TI&#xAD;LAK ME&#xAD;HTA, 15</h1>
    <h2>En&#xAD;tre&#xAD;pre&#xAD;neur, In&#xAD;dia</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201219/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-19"><time>2020-12-19</time></a>
        - <span>SPECIAL REPORT</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>When Ti­lak Me­hta was 12, he came up with a sim­ple busi­ness idea born out of frus­tra­tion that he could not get a par­cel de­liv­ery firm to send some books to his home in Mum­bai from an­other part of the city on the same day.</p>
    <p>He started Pa­pers N Parcels, a courier app that works with Mum­bai’s dab­bawalas – a highly ef­fi­cient net­work of food de­liv­ery­men – to pro­vide same­day de­liv­ery ser­vice at a rel­a­tively af­ford­able fee.</p>
    <p>To un­der­stand how the dab­bawalas op­er­ate, a young Ti­lak spent 15 days mov­ing around the city with them, ac­com­pa­nied by a grown-up trusted by his fa­ther, who worked in the lo­gis­tics industry.</p>
    <p>In Jan­uary this year, Ti­lak re­ceived In­dia’s Global Child Prodigy Award. And in April, he an­nounced on Twit­ter that he had sold his busi­ness to a multi­na­tional com­pany.</p>

